## 5.1 Overview

Local MCP servers extend AI apps with secure, controlled access to local resources. Uses Claude Desktop as example client. Server: `@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem` (Filesystem Server).

Capabilities: Read files/directories, create files/dirs, move/rename, search by name/content. ALL actions require explicit user approval.

## 5.2 Prerequisites
- Claude Desktop installed (macOS/Windows)
- Node.js (LTS recommended, verify with `node --version`)

## 5.3 Installation Steps

### Step 1: Open Claude Desktop Settings
Click Claude menu (system menu bar, NOT within Claude window) → "Settings..."

### Step 2: Access Developer Settings
Settings window → "Developer" tab → "Edit Config" button.
Creates/opens config file at:
- macOS: `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`
- Windows: `%APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json`

### Step 3: Configure Filesystem Server

macOS config:
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "filesystem": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/Users/username/Desktop", "/Users/username/Downloads"]
    }
  }
}
```

Windows config:
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "filesystem": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "C:\\Users\\username\\Desktop", "C:\\Users\\username\\Downloads"]
    }
  }
}
```

Replace `username` with actual username. Paths = directories server can access.

Config breakdown:
- `"filesystem"`: Friendly name in Claude Desktop
- `"command": "npx"`: Node.js npx runner
- `"-y"`: Auto-confirm package install
- `"@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem"`: Package name
- Remaining args: Allowed directories

SECURITY: Only grant access to directories you're comfortable with. Server runs with user account permissions.

### Step 4: Restart Claude Desktop
Save config → COMPLETELY quit Claude Desktop (Cmd+Q macOS, system tray Exit on Windows — closing window is NOT enough) → restart.

On success: MCP server indicator (hammer icon) appears in bottom-right of chat input. Click to see available tools.

## 5.4 Using the Filesystem Server

Example requests:
- "Can you write a poem and save it to my desktop?"
- "What work-related files are in my downloads folder?"
- "Please organize all images on my desktop into a new folder called 'Images'"

Before each file operation, Claude requests approval. Review carefully before approving.

## 5.5 Troubleshooting

### Server not showing up / hammer icon missing
1. Restart Claude Desktop completely
2. Check `claude_desktop_config.json` syntax
3. Verify paths are absolute (not relative)
4. Check logs: `~/Library/Logs/Claude` (macOS) or `%APPDATA%\Claude\logs` (Windows)
5. Test server manually:
   - macOS: `npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem /Users/username/Desktop /Users/username/Downloads`
   - Windows: `npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem C:\Users\username\Desktop C:\Users\username\Downloads`

### Getting logs from Claude Desktop
- `mcp.log`: General MCP connection logging
- `mcp-server-SERVERNAME.log`: stderr from named server
- macOS: `tail -n 20 -f ~/Library/Logs/Claude/mcp*.log`
- Windows: `type "%APPDATA%\Claude\logs\mcp*.log"`

### ENOENT error / `${APPDATA}` in paths on Windows
Add expanded `%APPDATA%` to `env` key:
```json
{
  "brave-search": {
    "command": "npx",
    "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-brave-search"],
    "env": {
      "APPDATA": "C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\",
      "BRAVE_API_KEY": "..."
    }
  }
}
```
If npm not installed globally: `npm install -g npm`

